issue.body: ### Self Checks - [x] I have read the [Contributing Guide](https://github.com/langgenius/dify/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md) and [Language Policy](https://github.com/langgenius/dify/issues/1542). - [x] This is only for bug report, if you would like to ask a question, please head to [Discussions](https://github.com/langgenius/dify/discussions/categories/general). - [x] I have searched for existing issues [search for existing issues](https://github.com/langgenius/dify/issues), including closed ones. - [x] I confirm that I am using English to submit this report, otherwise it will be closed. - [x] 【中文用户 & Non English User】请使用英语提交，否则会被关闭 ：） - [x] Please do not modify this template :) and fill in all the required fields. ### Dify version 1.7.2 ### Cloud or Self Hosted Self Hosted (Docker), Cloud ### Steps to reproduce 1. Install any official plugins which contains any tools with `create_link_message`. 2. Create workflow or chatflow and place the tools. 3. Try to invoke the tool which will return LINK type message. To easy to reproduce the issue, I've attached minimal tool here: [link_demo.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/21822961/link_demo.zip) (rename zip to difypkg to install) This is the minimal tool to reproduce: ```python from collections.abc import Generator from typing import Any from dify_plugin import Tool from dify_plugin.entities.tool import ToolInvokeMessage class LinkDemoTool(Tool): def _invoke(self, tool_parameters: dict[str, Any]) -> Generator[ToolInvokeMessage]: yield self.create_link_message("https://dify.ai/") ``` Affected official plugins are: ```bash $ grep -rE '^\s+yield self\.create_link_message' ./tools ./tools/hackernews/tools/get_story_info.py: yield self.create_link_message(story_url) ./tools/telegraph/tools/telegraph.py: yield self.create_link_message(ph_link) ./tools/spotify/tools/spotify_get_track.py: yield self.create_link_message(track_info["preview_url"]) ./tools/searchapi/tools/google.py: yield self.create_link_message(link=result) ./tools/searchapi/tools/google_jobs.py: yield self.create_link_message(link=result) ./tools/google_calendar/tools/create_event.py: yield self.create_link_message(created_event["htmlLink"]) ./tools/zoom/tools/zoom_update_meeting.py: yield self.create_link_message(updated_meeting["join_url"]) ./tools/zoom/tools/zoom_list_meetings.py: yield self.create_link_message(meeting["join_url"]) ./tools/zoom/tools/zoom_get_meeting.py: yield self.create_link_message(meeting_info["join_url"]) ./tools/zoom/tools/zoom_create_meeting.py: yield self.create_link_message(meeting_info["join_url"]) ./tools/wolframalpha/tools/wolframalpha.py: yield self.create_link_message(response_data["queryresult"]["sources"]["url"]) ./tools/twitter/tools/get_user_info.py: yield self.create_link_message(profile_url) ./tools/twitter/tools/send_tweet.py: yield self.create_link_message(f"https://twitter.com/user/status/{tweet_id}") ``` ### ✔️ Expected Behavior The link message has been returned. ### ❌ Actual Behavior ```bash Run failed: (psycopg2.errors.InvalidTextRepresentation) invalid input syntax for type uuid: "" LINE 3: WHERE tool_files.id = ''::UUID ^ [SQL: SELECT tool_files.id, tool_files.user_id, tool_files.tenant_id, tool_files.conversation_id, tool_files.file_key, tool_files.mimetype, tool_files.original_url, tool_files.name, tool_files.size FROM tool_files WHERE tool_files.id = %(id_1)s::UUID] [parameters: {'id_1': ''}] (Background on this error at: https://sqlalche.me/e/20/9h9h) ```

comment.body:
<!-- Answer -->
This is a confirmed regression in Dify v1.7.2 affecting all tools and plugins that use `create_link_message` to return generic URLs. The backend now incorrectly assumes every LINK message contains a Dify-managed file UUID, so when a generic URL is returned, it tries to query the database with an empty or invalid UUID, causing the SQL error you see. This impacts both official plugins and custom tools.

The root cause is a recent code change that extracts a supposed `tool_file_id` from the link URL and always queries the `tool_files` table, regardless of whether the link is actually a Dify file or just a regular URL. If the link isn't a Dify file, this results in an invalid UUID error ([details here](https://github.com/langgenius/dify/pull/18427)).

**Workaround:**  
A code-level fix is needed in the backend to only treat URLs as `tool_file_id` if they match the UUID format. Until an official fix is released, you could patch your local deployment to add a check before querying the database—only attempt the lookup if the extracted segment is a valid UUID. Otherwise, treat it as a generic link and skip the DB lookup.

There are currently no open pull requests addressing this regression, so monitoring future releases or patching locally is the best path forward for now.

pull_request.title: Add comprehensive GitHub Copilot instructions for Lamdera Elm development
pull_request.body:
This PR adds a comprehensive `.github/copilot-instructions.md` file that provides GitHub Copilot coding agents with detailed, validated instructions for working effectively in this Lamdera-based Elm accounting application.

## Key Features

**Exhaustively Validated Commands**: Every single command and workflow has been tested and timed to ensure reliability:
- Frontend/Backend compilation: ~30 seconds cold, <1 second warm
- Development server startup: ~45 seconds cold, <5 seconds warm  
- Code formatting and linting workflows

**Critical Timing Guidelines**: Includes explicit "NEVER CANCEL" warnings with specific timeout recommendations:
- Build commands: 60+ second timeouts for cold builds
- Server startup: 120+ second timeouts for initial launches
- All timing measurements based on actual test runs

**Complete Development Workflow**: Covers the full development lifecycle from initial setup through validation:
- Initial setup with Node.js 20 and Lamdera CLI installation
- Core build commands for Frontend and Backend modules
- Development server operation and validation
- Pre-commit validation checklist

**Manual Testing Requirements**: Emphasizes the critical importance of functional validation after code changes, including:
- HTTP response verification (`curl` commands provided)
- Complete user scenario testing requirements
- Application accessibility validation

**Project-Specific Guidance**: Tailored specifically for this Lamdera Elm application:
- Explains the Evergreen migration system for type changes
- Documents the unified full-stack development approach
- Covers Lamdera-specific deployment considerations
- Includes troubleshooting for common Lamdera issues

**Comprehensive Reference**: Provides detailed project structure documentation, expected command outputs, and troubleshooting guidance to minimize the need for additional context gathering.

The instructions follow an imperative tone throughout and prioritize known-working validation steps to ensure agents can work efficiently and reliably in this codebase.

Fixes #17.
